<div style="clear:both" /><div class="news">
<a name="news"></a><h2>News</h2>
<h3>HCSNet Priority Area: Human and Machine Perception and Action</h3>

<p>Ricky van der Zwan, this week's spotlight, is a leader of HCSNet's Human and
Machine Perception and Action Priority Area. Evidence accumulates that
perception and action are linked, and that the process of producing actions
and reading actions by others is one of neural mirroring or simulation.
Despite the coupling of perception and action in humans, perception and
action are often considered as separate domains of research. The way that
humans attend to particular information from the wide array available, and
use this information to guide and direct action, is not only of theoretical
and practical interest for studies on human behaviour and human movement,
but also for human studies of when such behaviours go awry in such
conditions as motor disorders, and studies of machine-based learning and
robotics.  This priority area aims to open up exploration of these
interactions. See the Priority Areas web pages at
<a href="http://www.hcsnet.edu.au/priorityareas">http://www.hcsnet.edu.au/priorityareas</a> for more information.</p>

